tity among American Indians. He examines the origins of Shoshone and Bannock ethnicity, follows these peoples through a period of declining autonomy vis-a-vis the United States government, and finally puts their experience and the Ghost Dances within the larger context of identity formation and emerging nationalism which marked United States history in the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBannock IndiansxEthnic identity. 0aBannock IndiansxReligion. 0aBannock IndiansxRites and ceremonies. 0aGhost dancexHistoryx19th century. 0aGhost dancexHistoryy19th century. 0aShoshoni IndiansxEthnic identity. 0aShoshoni IndiansxReligion. 0aShoshoni IndiansxRites and ceremonies. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941724423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520941724.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles